 style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Mountaineer Casino Racetrack and Resort]], [[Chester]], West Virginia, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|1\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|1\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Jon Hill\n|{{abbr|TKO|Techncal Knockout}}\n|1 (4), {{small|1:01}}\n|Jan 26, 2013\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Serbian American Cultural Center, [[Weirton, West Virginia]], U.S.}}\n|\n|}\n\n== Writing career ==\nOn Feb 17th, 2017, Latimore released ''Not Caring What Anyone Thinks Is A Superpower: Insight From A Heavyweight Boxer''. The book explores areas of his life that, while making major improvements, Latimore put time into to \u201cdevelop the ability to shrug off your critics and not let them drag you back down to their level.\u201d<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn Dec 23rd, 2018, Latimore released ''Sober Letters To My Drunken Self''. The book is written to help people having difficulty with the emotional struggles involved with getting control of their drinking. The book was released on the 5 year anniversary of Latimore\u2019s sobriety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43315143-sober-letters-to-my-drunken-self|title=Sober Letters To My Drunken Self|website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref>\n\nOn Dec 25th, 2018, Latimore released ''Engagement Is The New Cocaine: The Art And Science Of Writing Awesomely Addictive Tweets''. The book teaches the benefits of using stylistic devices to bolster social media engagement. The guide has been generally well reviewed.\n\n== Personal life ==\nLatimore is a strong advocate for sobriety and overcoming pornography addiction. He's been sober since December 23, 2013. He holds a Bachelor of the Arts degree in Physics from [[Duquesne University]], which he did not attain until age 33. He\u2019s a veteran of The [[United States Army National Guard]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goingdeepsummit.com/ed-latimore|title=Ed Latimore|website=Going Deep Summit}}</ref> He also is an avid online and over-the-board chess player, having been featured in American Chess Magazine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://store.chessgames.com/american-chess-magazine-issue-008.html|title=AMERICAN CHESS MAGAZINE Issue no. 8|website=store.chessgames.com}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Latimore, Ed}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox boxer|name=Ed Latimore|image=BoxingWorkout.jpg|nickname=Black Magic|weight=[[Heavyweight]]|height=6 ft 1 in|reach=76 in|nationality=American|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1985|2|15|mf=y}}|birth_place=[[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania, U.S.|style=[[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]|boxrec=641641|total=15|wins=13|KO=7|losses=1|draws=1}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| occupation = [[Author]], [[marketer]], [[entrepreneur]]\n| alma_mater = [[Duquesne University]], B.A. Physics\n| genre = [[Nonfiction]]\n| notableworks = '''Not Caring What Other People Think Is A Superpower: Insights From A Heavyweight Boxer'''(2017)<br /> '''Sober Letters To My Drunken Self'''(2018)<br /> '''Engagement Is The New Cocaine: The Art and Science Of Writing Awesomely Addictive Tweets'''(2018)\n}}\n\n'''Edward Ashley Latimore, Jr.''' (born February 15th, 1985 in Pittsburgh, PA) is a retired American professional boxer (13-1-1).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/641641|title=BoxRec: Ed Latimore|website=boxrec.com}}</ref>, [[influencer]], and author<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Ed-Latimore/e/B01M158PKD?ref=sr_ntt_srch_lnk_1&qid=1582371228&sr=8-1|title=Ed Latimore|website=www.amazon.com}}</ref>. His final professional fight was December 17, 2016.\n\nHe launched his blog Mind and Fist<ref>www.edlatimore.com</ref> in 2013, focusing on the difficult lessons he learned from growing up in public housing projects, overcoming alcohol and pornography addiction, and general self-improvement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/boxing/article/3051195/how-former-heavyweight-boxer-ed-latimore-found-himself-sobriety-and|title=How former heavyweight boxer Ed Latimore found himself and a new life|date=February 20, 2020|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nHe has published two books. ''Not Caring What Other People Think Is A Superpower: Insights From A Heavyweight Boxer'' and ''Sober Letters To My Drunken Self'' along with a writing and marketing guide for social media titled ''Engagement Is The New Cocaine: The Art And Science Of Writing Awesomely Addictive Tweets''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/coinmonks/how-to-twitter-f0f6f339c40e|title=HOW TO TWITTER|date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>.\n\nHe's been a guest on [[Jordan Harbinger|''The Jordan Harbinger Show'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordanharbinger.com/ed-latimore-the-superpower-of-ignoring-social-approval/|title=Ed Latimore &#124; The Superpower of Ignoring Social Approval|date=February 27, 2018|website=Jordan Harbinger}}</ref>, ''The Art of Manliness''<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.artofmanliness.com/articles/podcast-345-not-caring-people-think-superpower/|title=Podcast: Interview with Heavyweight Boxer Ed Latimore &#124; Art of Manliness|date=October 6, 2017}}</ref>, ''Farnam Street''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fs.blog/ed-latimore/|title=Ed Latimore: The Warrior Poet and the Secret to a Happy Life [The Knowledge Project Ep. #21]|website=Farnam Street}}</ref>, and [[Scott Adams|''Coffee with Scott Adams'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scottadamssays.com/2019/03/21/episode-459-scott-adams-talking-with-writer-boxer-brilliant-guy-edlatimore-on-success/|title=Episode 459 Scott Adams: Talking With Writer, Boxer, Brilliant Guy @EdLatimore on Success|date=March 21, 2019|website=Scott Adams' Blog}}</ref> to discuss sobriety, boxing, growing up in poverty, and physics.\n\nHe's also been featured on [[Ryan Holiday|Ryan Holiday's]] blog ''The Daily Stoic''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailystoic.com/edward-latimore/|title=Heavyweight Boxer Edward Latimore on Self-Control, Life Lessons from Seneca and Getting Better Every Day|date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> as well as in James Clear's international best seller, ''Atomic Habits''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=XfFvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA286&lpg=PA286&dq=ed+latimore+james+clear&source=bl&ots=uxCKEmLMcL&sig=ACfU3U01INY3ZvdJYCLAPGHt20acscTJmQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiS-ZSRuOPnAhXRUMAKHTqcA0YQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=ed+latimore+james+clear&f=false|title=Atomic Habits: Tiny Changes, Remarkable Results : an Easy & Proven Way to Build Good Habits & Break Bad Ones|first=James|last=Clear|date=February 22, 2018|publisher=Penguin|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nLatimore was born on February 15th, 1985 in Pittsburgh, PA. He only saw his father a few times a year and was raised primarily by his mother. The family was poor and lived in the [[Hill District (Pittsburgh)|Hill District housing projects]] until they were demolished in 1995. The family then moved across town to the [[Northview Heights (Pittsburgh)|Northview Heights housing project]] where he lived until he was 18 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pghcitypaper.com/pittsburgh/the-sophisticated-pugilist-pittsburghs-ed-latimore-wants-to-be-the-heavyweight-champion-of-the-world-and-a-whole-lot-more/Content?oid=1971627|title=The Sophisticated Pugilist: Pittsburgh\u2019s Ed Latimore wants to be the heavyweight champion of the world, and a whole lot more|first=Charlie|last=Deitch|website=Pittsburgh City Paper}}</ref>\n\n== Amateur Boxing Career ==\nLatimore started amateur boxing in 2007 when he was 22 years old. He won the Pennsylvania State National Golden Gloves in 2011 at the 201+ lb weight class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newpittsburghcourier.com/2011/04/08/bradley-and-latimore-stars-shine-brightest-at-pittsburgh-golden-gloves-championships/|title=Bradley and Latimore stars shine brightest at Pittsburgh Golden Gloves Championships|date=April 8, 2011|website=New Pittsburgh Courier}}</ref> He also became a national amateur boxing champion by winning the National Police Athletic League boxing tournament in Toledo, Ohio at the 201+ lb weight class.<ref>https://www.teamusa.org/usa-boxing/features/2011/october/03/2011-national-pal-results</ref> He holds notable amateur victories over former IBF heavyweight champion [[Charles Martin (boxer)|Charles Martin]] and 2012 United States Olympian and two-time title challenger [[Dominic Breazeale]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://archive.boxing.media/ed_latimore_boxings_renaissance_man.html|title=Ed Latimore: Boxing\u2019s Renaissance Man - Boxing.com|website=archive.boxing.media}}</ref>\n\nLatimore was also a member of now deceased media mogul Michael King\u2019s ''All-American Heavyweights'' boxer development program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/47127895|title=ALL AMERICAN HEAVYWEIGHTS - Promo|website=Vimeo}}</ref>, where he lived and trained alongside Martin and Breazeale in Carson, CA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/tv-mogul-michael-king-moves-235843052--box.html|title=TV mogul Michael King moves into boxing promotion|website=sports.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\n== Professional Boxing Career ==\nLatimore started his professional boxing career on January 26, 2013 with a 3rd round TKO victory over 4-1 southpaw Jon Hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Ed_Latimore_vs._Jon_Hill|title=Ed Latimore vs. Jon Hill - BoxRec|website=boxrec.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter 6 professional fights, Latimore was signed by the [[Jay-Z]] owned sports promotion company [[Roc Nation Sports]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nLatimore\u2019s first televised fight was against [[:de:Trey_Morrison|Trey Lippe-Morrison]], the son of late [[WBO]] Heavyweight Champion [[Tommy Morrison]]. He suffered his first career loss by a devastating first round TKO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/%20/tommy-morrisons-son-demolishes-ed-latimore-one-round--109094|title=Tommy Morrison's Son Demolishes Ed Latimore in One Round|website=BoxingScene.com}}</ref>\n\nLatimore fought one more time in 2016 to a draw against Willis Lockett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxerlist.com/boxer/ed-latimore/472491/|title=\u2022 Ed Latimore Black Magic boxer \u2022|website=www.boxerlist.com}}</ref>\n\n== Professional boxing record ==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary|draws=1|nc=|ko-wins=7|ko-losses=1|dec-wins=5|dec-losses=|dq-wins=1|dq-losses=}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n|-\n|15\n|{{draw}}Draw\n|13\u20131-1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Willis Lockett\n|{{abbr|SD|Split draw}}\n|6\n|Dec 17, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Mountaineer Casino Ballroom,]], [[New Cumberland, West Virginia|New Cumberland]], West Virginia, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|14\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|13-1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} [[Trey Lippe-Morrison]]\n|KO\n|1 (6), {{small|2:19}}\n|Sep 23, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Buffalo Run Casino]], [[Miami]], Oklahoma, US}}\n|\n|-\n|13\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|13\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Juan Goode\n|SD\n|6\n|Jul 15, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Rivers Casino,]], [[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|12\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|12\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Hassan Lee\n|TKO\n|6\n|Apr 23, 2016\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Mountaineer Casino Ballroom,]], [[New Cumberland, West Virginia|New Cumberland]], West Virginia, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|11\