30\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Rubin Williams\n|KO\n|1 (4), {{small|1:05}}\n|Mar 28, 2014\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Serbian American Cultural Center,]], [[Weirton]], West Virginia, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|3\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|3\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Christopher White\n|{{abbr|KO|Knockout}}\n|2 (4), {{small|3:00}}\n|Apr 20, 2013\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Serbian American Cultural Center,]], [[Weirton]], West Virginia, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|2\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|2\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Donnie Crawford\n|TKO\n|2 (4), {{small|1:22}}\n|Apr 6, 2013\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Mountaineer Casino Racetrack and Resort]], [[Chester]], West Virginia, U.S.}}\n|\n|-\n|1\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|1\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Jon Hill\n|{{abbr|TKO|Techncal Knockout}}\n|1 (4), {{small|1:01}}\n|Jan 26, 2013\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Serbian American Cultural Center, [[Weirton, West Virginia]], U.S.}}\n|\n|}\n\n== Writing Career ==\nOn Feb 17th, 2017, Latimore released ''Not Caring What Anyone Thinks Is A Superpower: Insight From A Heavyweight Boxer''. The book explores areas of his life that, while making major improvements, Latimore put time into to \u201cdevelop the ability to shrug off your critics and not let them drag you back down to their level.\u201d<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nOn Dec 23rd, 2018, Latimore released ''Sober Letters To My Drunken Self''. The book is written to help people having difficulty with the emotional struggles involved with getting control of their drinking. The book was released on the 5 year anniversary of Latimore\u2019s sobriety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43315143-sober-letters-to-my-drunken-self|title=Sober Letters To My Drunken Self|website=www.goodreads.com}}</ref>\n\nOn Dec 25th, 2018, Latimore released ''Engagement Is The New Cocaine: The Art And Science Of Writing Awesomely Addictive Tweets''. The book teaches the benefits of using stylistic devices to bolster social media engagement. The guide has been generally well reviewed.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nLatimore is a strong advocate for sobriety and overcoming pornography addiction. He's been sober since December 23, 2013. He holds a Bachelor of the Arts degree in Physics from [[Duquesne University]], which he did not attain until age 33. He\u2019s a veteran of The [[United States Army National Guard]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goingdeepsummit.com/ed-latimore|title=Ed Latimore|website=Going Deep Summit}}</ref>. He also is an avid online and over-the-board chess player, having been featured in American Chess Magazine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://store.chessgames.com/american-chess-magazine-issue-008.html|title=AMERICAN CHESS MAGAZINE Issue no. 8|website=store.chessgames.com}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Latimore, Ed}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_Latimore"}
{"title_page": "Listed buildings in Ellenhall", "text_new": "[[Ellenhall]] is a [[civil parish]] in the [[Borough of Stafford]], [[Staffordshire]], England.  It contains five [[Listed building#England and Wales|listed buildings]] that are recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]]. Of these, two are at Grade&nbsp;II*, the middle of the three grades, and the others are at Grade&nbsp;II, the lowest grade. The parish contains the villages of Ellenhall and [[Ranton, Staffordshire|Ranton]] and the surrounding countryside.  The listed buildings consist of a church, a cross in the churchyard, the surviving tower of an abbey church, a house, and a milepost.\n__NOTOC__\n==Key==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Grade\n! Criteria{{sfn|Historic England|ps=none}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|II*\n| Particularly important buildings of more than special interest\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|II\n| Buildings of national importance and special interest\n|}\n\n==Buildings==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; border:0; text-align:left; line-height:150%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:150px\" |Name and location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:100px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Photograph\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:120px\" |Date\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:650px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:50px\" |Grade\n|-\n|St Mary's Church<br/><small>{{coord|52.83604|-2.23721|type:landmark|name=St Mary's Church}}</small>\n|[[File:Ellenhall church.JPG|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1150|12th century}}\n|The [[chancel]] was largely rebuilt in 1683, the [[nave]] was rebuilt and the tower added in 1757, and the church was [[Victorian restoration|restored]] in 1885\u201388 by [[Charles Lynam]] when the porch was added.  The tower and south wall of the nave are in brick, and the rest of the church is in stone, and the roof is tiled.  The church consists of a nave, a southwest porch, a chancel, a northeast [[vestry]], and a west tower.  The tower has three stages, [[molding (architecture)|moulded]] [[string course]]s, clock faces, and an [[embattled]] [[parapet]].  In the chancel is a [[Norman architecture|Norman]] north window, and the other windows are [[Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]].{{sfnp|Pevsner|1974|pp=128\u2013129|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1242638|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Churchyard cross<br/><small>{{coord|52.83597|-2.23727|type:landmark|name=Churchyard cross}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1400|Medieval}}\n|The cross is in the churchyard of St Mary's Church.  It is in stone, and has a square [[chamfer]]ed base on three steps.  On the base is a tapering shaft, the upper part of which is modern.  On the top is a [[crucifix]] dating from the 19th&nbsp;century.  The cross is a [[scheduled monument]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1259925|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1012661|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Tower, [[Ranton Abbey]]<br/><small>{{coord|52.81580|-2.24152|type:landmark|name=Tower, Ranton Abbey}}</small>\n|[[File:Ranton abbey.JPG|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1450|15th century}}\n|The tower is the only remaining part of the church of the abbey.  It is in stone, and has angle [[buttress]]es, a west doorway and a five-light west window, both with decorated [[hood mould]]s, a high arch to the former [[nave]] with [[embattled]] [[capital (architecture)|capitals]], two-light bell openings, and a [[saltire]] [[frieze]] under an embattled [[parapet]].  A portion of the nave wall also survives, and this contains a [[Norman architecture|Norman]] doorway with a continuous roll-[[molding (architecture)|moulding]].  The site on which the tower stands is a [[scheduled monument]].{{sfnp|Pevsner|1974|pp=224\u2013225|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1259926|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1011053|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Ellenhall Hall<br/><small>{{coord|52.83626|-2.23797|type:landmark|name=Ellenhall Hall}}</small>\n|[[File:Ellenhall Hall.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1650|17th century}}\n|The house, which was altered later, is in brick with corner [[buttress]]es and a tile roof.  There are two storeys and an attic, a front with three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], two [[gable]]s, and a gabled porch.  The windows are [[casement window|casements]] with cambered heads, and there is a blind circular window in each gable.  The left return has three bays, and contains two [[cant (architecture)|canted]] [[bay window]]s.{{sfnp|Historic England|1242639|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Milepost<br/><small>{{coord|52.82047|-2.25015|type:landmark|name=Milepost}}</small>\n|[[File:Milepost 7 miles from Stafford.jpg|50px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1850|Mid 19th century}}\n|The milepost is on the north side of the [[Stafford]] to [[Newport, Shropshire|Newport]] road (B5405 road).  It is in [[cast iron]] and has a triangular plan and a sloping top.  The milepost is inscribed \"Parish of Seighford\" and the distances to London, Stafford and Newport.{{sfnp|Historic England|1258136|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{portal|Staffordshire}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1242638|desc= Church of St Mary, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1259925|desc= Churchyard Cross, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1012661|desc= Churchyard Cross, St Mary's churchyard, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1259926|desc= Tower at Ranton Abbey, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1011053|desc= Ranton Priory: a moate