81580|-2.24152|type:landmark|name=Tower, Ranton Abbey}}</small>\n|[[File:Ranton abbey.JPG|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1450|15th century}}\n|The tower is the only remaining part of the church of the abbey.  It is in stone, and has angle [[buttress]]es, a west doorway and a five-light west window, both with decorated [[hood mould]]s, a high arch to the former [[nave]] with [[embattled]] [[capital (architecture)|capitals]], two-light bell openings, and a [[saltire]] [[frieze]] under an embattled [[parapet]].  A portion of the nave wall also survives, and this contains a [[Norman architecture|Norman]] doorway with a continuous roll-[[molding (architecture)|moulding]].  The site on which the tower stands is a [[scheduled monument]].{{sfnp|Pevsner|1974|pp=224\u2013225|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1259926|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1011053|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Ellenhall Hall<br/><small>{{coord|52.83626|-2.23797|type:landmark|name=Ellenhall Hall}}</small>\n|[[File:Ellenhall Hall.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1650|17th century}}\n|The house, which was altered later, is in brick with corner [[buttress]]es and a tile roof.  There are two storeys and an attic, a front with three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], two [[gable]]s, and a gabled porch.  The windows are [[casement window|casements]] with cambered heads, and there is a blind circular window in each gable.  The left return has three bays, and contains two [[cant (architecture)|canted]] [[bay window]]s.{{sfnp|Historic England|1242639|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Milepost<br/><small>{{coord|52.82047|-2.25015|type:landmark|name=Milepost}}</small>\n|[[File:Milepost 7 miles from Stafford.jpg|50px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1850|Mid 19th century}}\n|The milepost is on the north side of the [[Stafford]] to [[Newport, Shropshire|Newport]] road (B5405 road).  It is in [[cast iron]] and has a triangular plan and a sloping top.  The milepost is inscribed \"Parish of Seighford\" and the distances to London, Stafford and Newport.{{sfnp|Historic England|1258136|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{portal|Staffordshire}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|20em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1242638|desc= Church of St Mary, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1259925|desc= Churchyard Cross, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1012661|desc= Churchyard Cross, St Mary's churchyard, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1259926|desc= Tower at Ranton Abbey, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1011053|desc= Ranton Priory: a moated Augustinian priory, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1242639|desc= Ellenhall Hall, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1258136|desc= Milepost Stafford-Newport Road 7 miles from Stafford, Ellenhall|access-date= 20 November 2019|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{Citation | author = Historic England | title = Listed Buildings | url = http://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/what-is-designation/listed-buildings/ |accessdate= 20 November 2019}}\n*{{Citation | last =Pevsner | first =Nikolaus | authorlink =Nikolaus Pevsner | series= The Buildings of England| title =Staffordshire |edition= | publisher =[[Penguin Books]] | year =1974 | location = Harmondsworth|  isbn = 0-14-071046-9}}\n{{Refend}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellenhall}}\n[[Category:Lists of listed buildings in Staffordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Shonebrooks", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling churchWP:TYPO", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Listed_buildings_in_Ellenhall"}
{"title_page": "Curl-crested aracari", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| image = Curl-crested Aracari.jpg\n| image_caption=At [[Riverbanks Zoo]], US\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22682041/0 |title=''Pteroglossus beauharnaesii'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Pteroglossus\n| species = beauharnaesii\n| authority = [[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]], 1832\n| synonyms = \n* ''Beauharnaisius beauharnaesii''\n* ''Pteroglossus Beauharnaesii''\n}}\n\nThe '''curl-crested aracari''', '''curl-crested ara\u00e7ari''' or '''curly-crested aracari''' (''Pteroglossus beauharnaesii'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Ramphastidae]], the [[toucan]]s. The species was [[Species description|first described]] by [[Johann Georg Wagler]] in 1832.\n\n==Description==\nIt measures {{convert|40|\u2013|45|cm|abbr=on}} long and weighs {{convert|190|-|280|g|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/ramphastidae.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-08-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819114100/http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/ramphastidae.htm |archivedate=2007-08-19 }}</ref> On account of its relatively long tail and curly [[Crest (feathers)|crest]] (the latter only visible up close), it was formerly placed in the [[monotypic]] [[genus]] '''''Beauharnaisius'''''.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe curl-crested aracari is found in the south-western section of the [[Amazon Basin]], with the [[Amazon River]] being its northern range limit. Near the Amazon River, its range extends east to about the [[Madeira River]], while in the southern half of its [[range (biology)|range]] it extends east to the [[Xingu River]]. It is generally rare to uncommon, but regularly seen at several localities, including the [[Tambopata National Reserve]] in Peru, the [[Noel Kempff Mercado National Park]] in Bolivia, and the [[Cristalino State Park]] near [[Alta Floresta]] in Brazil. Its natural [[habitat]] is [[tropical]] moist lowland [[forest]]s.\n\n==Behaviour==\nIt is primarily a [[frugivore]], but will also take nestlings of birds such as the [[yellow-rumped cacique]].\n\n==Status and conservation==\nDue to its extensive range, it is considered to be of [[least concern]] by [[BirdLife International]] and consequently the [[IUCN]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"167px\" heights=\"125px\" >\nImage:Pteroglossus beauharnaesii-Gould.jpg|By [[John Gould]]\nImage:Curl-crested Aracari RWD4.jpg|At [[San Diego Zoo]], US\nImage:Curl-crested Aracari RWD3.jpg|At San Diego Zoo\n</gallery><br />\n==Aviculture==\nThe curl-crested aracari is a popular pet toucan and the most frequently kept 'small toucan' after the [[green aracari]]. It requires a large cage for its size, as well as several perches and toys due to its active nature. Curl crested aracaris like all toucans, need a high-fruit diet which without they are susceptible to a disease of excessive iron storage.\n\n== Literature ==\n* [[John Gould]] and [[Henry Constantine Richter]]: ''A Monograph of the Ramphaastidae, or Family of Toucans'', London 1854\n** new edition: with 51 coloured tables and a preface by [[Jonathan Elphick]]: [[Taschen]], K\u00f6ln 2011 {{ISBN|978-3-8365-0524-6}}\n\n==References==\n<!-- BulletinOfTheBritishOrnithologistsClub128:53. -->\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Commons-inline|Pteroglossus beauharnaesii}}\n* [http://www.arthurgrosset.com/sabirds/curl-crestedaracari.html Curl-crested Ara\u00e7ari (''Pteroglossus beauharnaesii'').] arthurgrosset.com. Accessed 2008-07-29\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20130126092444/http://ibc.hbw.com/ibc/phtml/especie.phtml?idEspecie=3723 Curl-crested Aracari videos] on the Internet Bird Collection\n*[http://vireo.acnatsci.org/search.html?Form=Search&SEARCHBY=Scientific&KEYWORDS=pteroglossus+beauharnaesii&showwhat=images&AGE=All&SEX=All&ACT=All&Search=Search&VIEW=All&ORIENTATION=All&RESULTS=24 \"Curly-crested Aracari\" photo gallery] VIREO [http://vireo.acnatsci.org/species_image.php?species=Pteroglossus+beauharnaesii Photo-High Res]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071026040343/http://www.tropicalbirding.com/tripReports/TR_Pant-Amaz-Oct2006/ccaracari.jpg Photo-High Res]; [https://web.archive.org/web/20070714165540/http://www.tropicalbirding.com/tripReports/TR_Pant-Amaz-Oct2006/TR_Pant-Amaz-Oct2006.html Trip Report] tropicalbirding\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060511163539/http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/images/curl_crested_aracari2.jpg Photo-Medium Res--(Dorsal View)]; [https://web.archive.org/web/20070819114100/http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/ramphastidae.htm Article] nashvillezoo.org&mdash;\"Ramphastidae\"\n\n<!--see a good RangeMap/maps, lists, etc at: \"www.natureserve.org\"(then 'InfoNatura')....for the species, only category shown is: \"Permanent Resident\"-->\n\n{{Ramphastidae}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q833143}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:aracari, curl-crested}}\n[[Category:Pteroglossus|curl-crested aracari]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Amazon Basin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Peruvian Amazon]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Bolivian Amazon]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1832|curl-crested aracari]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Piciformes-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| image = Curl-crested Aracari.jpg\n| image_caption=At [[Riverbanks Zoo]], US\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22682041/0 |title=''Pteroglossus beauharnaesii'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Pteroglossus\n| species = beauharnaesii\n| authority = [[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]], 1832\n| synonyms = \n* ''Beauharnaisius beauharnaesii''\n* ''Pteroglossus Beauharnaesii''\n}}\n\nThe '''curl-crested aracari''', '''curl-crested ara\u00e7ari''' or '''curly-crested aracari''' (''Pteroglossus beauharnaesii'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Ramphastidae]], the [[toucan]]s. The species was [[Species description|first described]] by [[Johann Georg Wagler]] in 1832.\n\n==Description==\nIt measures {{convert|40|\u2013|45|cm|abbr=on}} long and weighs {{convert|190|-|280|g|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/ramphastidae.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-08-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819114100/http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/ramphastidae.htm |archivedate=2007-08-19 }}</ref> On account of its relatively long tail and curly [[Crest (feathers)|crest]] (the latter only visible up close), it was formerly placed in the [[monotypic]] [[genus]] '''''Beauharnaisius'''''.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe curl-crested aracari is found in the south-western section of the [[Amazon Basin]], with the [[Amazon River]] being its northern range limit. Near the Amazon River, its range extends east to about the [[Madeira River]], while in the southern half of its [[range (biology)|range]] it extends east to the [[Xingu River]]. It is generally rare to uncommon, but regularly seen at several localities, including the [[Tambopata National Reserve]] in Peru, the [[Noel Kempff Mercado National Park]] in Bolivia, and the [[Cristalino State Park]] near [[Alta Floresta]] in Brazil. Its natural [[habitat]] is [[tropical]] moist lowland [[forest]]s.\n\n==Behaviour==\nIt is primarily a [[frugivore]], but will also take nestlings of birds such as the [[yellow-rumped cacique]].\n\n==Status and conservation==\nDue to its extensive range, it is considered to be of [[least concern]] by [[BirdLife International]] and consequently the [[IUCN]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"167px\" heights=\"125px\" >\nImage:Pteroglossus beauharnaesii-Gould.jpg|By [[John Gould]]\nImage:Curl-crested Aracari RWD4.jpg|At [[San Diego Zoo]], US\nImage:Curl-crested Aracari RWD3.jpg|At San Diego Zoo\n</gallery><br />\n==Aviculture==\nThe curl-crested aracari is a popular pet toucan and the most frequently kept \"small toucan\" after the [[green aracari]]. It requires a large cage for its size, as well as several perches and toys due to its active nature. Curl crested aracaris like all toucans, need a high-fruit diet which without they are susceptible to a disease of excessive iron storage.\n\n== Literature ==\n* [[John Gould]] and [[Henry Constantine Richter]]: ''A Monograph of the Ramphaastidae, or Family of Toucans'', London 1854\n** new edition: with 51 coloured tables and a preface by [[Jonathan Elphick]]: [[Taschen]], K\u00f6ln 2011 {{ISBN|978-3-8365-0524-6}}\n\n==References==\n<!-- BulletinOfTheBritishOrnithologistsClub128:53. -->\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Commons-inline|Pteroglossus beauharnaesii}}\n* [http://www.arthurgrosset.com/sabirds/curl-crestedaracari.html Curl-crested Ara\u00e7ari (''Pteroglossus beauharnaesii'').] arthurgrosset.com. Accessed 2008-07-29\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20130126092444/http://ibc.hbw.com/ibc/phtml/especie.phtml?idEspecie=3723 Curl-crested Aracari videos] on the Internet Bird Collection\n*[http://vireo.acnatsci.org/search.html?Form=Search&SEARCHBY=Scientific&KEYWORDS=pteroglossus+beauharnaesii&showwhat=images&AGE=All&SEX=All&ACT=All&Search=Search&VIEW=All&ORIENTATION=All&RESULTS=24 \"Curly-crested Aracari\" photo gallery] VIREO [http://vireo.acnatsci.org/species_image.php?species=Pteroglossus+beauharnaesii Photo-High Res]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071026040343/http://www.tropicalbirding.com/tripReports/TR_Pant-Amaz-Oct2006/ccaracari.jpg Photo-High Res]; [https://web.archive.org/web/20070714165540/http://www.tropicalbirding.com/tripReports/TR_Pant-Amaz-Oct2006/TR_Pant-Amaz-Oct2006.html Trip Report] tropicalbirding\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060511163539/http://www.nashvillezoo.org/piciformes/images/curl_crested_aracari2.jpg Photo-Mediu