{"title_page": "Ed Gillespie (sustainability professional)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Edward Roger Martin Gillespie\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 28 June 1972{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n| birth_place   = {{Nowrap|Norfolk, England, UK{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}}}\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Inspirational keynote speaker and futurist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Co-Founded wearefuterra.com, Director of Greenpeace UK\n| notable_works = wearefuterra.com\n}}\n\n'''Ed Gillespie''' is a British environmental entrepreneur, inspirational keynote speaker, futurist and author. His focus is on [[sustainability]] and innovation.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nHe grew up in Norfolk, attending Norwich School. Afterwards he was a volunteer for [[Project Trust]] as a teacher in Above Rocks, [[Jamaica]]. He completed an BSc in [[marine biology]] at the [[University of Wales]] and continued in this discipline by undertaking a MSc in Marine Resource Development and Protection at [[Heriot-Watt University]].\n\nAfter this his focus shifted to business as he enrolled in a Professional Masters in Leadership for Sustainable Development at [[Middlesex University]], a course run by sustainable development charity Forum for the Future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forumforthefuture.org/masters-course-f4fma |title=Leadership for Sustainable Development |publisher=Forum for the Future |accessdate=2015-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219144138/https://www.forumforthefuture.org/masters-course-f4fma |archive-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While there he met Townsend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/small-business-network/2017/sep/20/businesses-on-the-couch-the-co-founders-in-couples-therapy|title=Businesses on the couch: the co-founders in couples' therapy|last=Lock|first=Helen|date=2017-09-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-10-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nEd started his professional career as an Environmental Development Manager at [[Transport for London|London Transport]]. Before this he had worked for the Survival [[Natural History]] Film Unit and as a [[marine biologist]] in [[Australia]], [[New Caledonia]] and [[Orkney]].\n\nIn 2001, he co-founded Futerra Sustainability Communications with [[Solitaire Townsend]]. He left the business in January 2019<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/small-business-network/2017/sep/20/businesses-on-the-couch-the-co-founders-in-couples-therapy|title=Businesses on the couch: the co-founders in couples' therapy|last=Lock|first=Helen|date=2017-09-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> to pursue other radical opportunities in international public speaking through the London Speaker Bureau,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonspeakerbureau.com/speaker-profile/ed-gillespie/|website=londonspeakerbureau.com|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> with the Forward Institute - where he works as a facilitator on responsible leadership development<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forward.institute/team-board|title=Team & Board|website=Forward Institute|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> and with disruptive, purpose-led start-up businesses including through his own ethical business accelerator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearefuterra.com/2018/06/global-goals-accelerator/|title=Global Goals Accelerator \u22c6 Futerra|date=2018-06-25|website=Futerra|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007/8, he traveled around the world without flying, during which he wrote a regular popular column for the Guardian/Observer - 'The Slow Traveller'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2007/mar/18/green.ethicalholidays.escape|title=The slow traveller: A bumpy start|last=Gillespie|first=Ed|date=2007-03-18|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> His passion for slow travel led him to invest in, and become Chairman of, European Rail Business [[Loco2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://loco2.com/about/team |title=team |publisher=Loco2 |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> This business was sold to SNCF in 2017.<ref>{{Citation|title=Loco2|date=2019-11-06|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Loco2&oldid=924860107|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nEd has held a number of Senior Advisory positions and Directorships. These include as a non-executive Director for Zero Carbon Food,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerocarbonfood.co.uk/team/ |title=The Team &#124; Zero Carbon FoodZero Carbon Food |publisher=Zerocarbonfood.co.uk |date=2014-01-24 |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> he was a London Sustainable Development Commissioner for several years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonsdc.org/lsdc/commissioners/ed-gillespie.aspx |title=Ed Gillespie |publisher=Londonsdc.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>  was a Director of carbon emissions campaigning organisation [[Sandbag (non-profit organisation)|Sandbag]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandbag.org.uk/whoweare/ |title=Who we are |publisher=Sandbag |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326040618/http://www.sandbag.org.uk/whoweare/ |archive-date=26 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and an investor in Foodtrade.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.foodtrade.com/frucool/ |title=ed gillespie |publisher=FoodTrade |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHe is currently a Director at Greenpeace UK,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenpeace.org.uk/about-greenpeace/board-of-directors/|title=Board of directors|website=Greenpeace UK|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> a Trustee at Energy Revolution<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.energy-revolution.org.uk/trustees/ed-gillespie/|title=Ed Gillespie|website=Energy Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> and an investor in a wide range of 'gamechanging' entrepreneurial businesses including Panda Packaging,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pandapackaging.co.uk/|website=www.pandapackaging.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> Piclo,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://piclo.energy/|title=piclo.energy|website=piclo.energy|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> Raw Bottles,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raw-bottles.org/|title=RAW Bottles|website=Realising Another World|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> Bennaman,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bennamann.com/|title=Bennamann Ltd \u2013 Bennamann creates solutions that transform the biomethane value chain.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> Engaged Tracking,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engagedtracking.com/|title=Engaged Tracking {{!}} Climate Portfolio Optimisation|website=EngagedTracking|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> Common  Objective<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commonobjective.co/|title=Sustainable Fashion {{!}} Do Fashion Better {{!}} Common Objective|website=www.commonobjective.co|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> and Small Robot Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smallrobotcompany.com/|title=Small Robot Company|website=Small Robot Company|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nAlong with fellow futurist [[Mark Stevenson]] he is half of the Futurenauts at the [https://www.atlasofthefuture.org Atlas of the Future,] and has both [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V8oYY_S8q7k spoken at] and co-hosted their annual [https://atlasofthefuture.org/fixing2019/ Fixing the Future] event in Barcelona.\n\n== Publications and public speaking ==\nEd is a regular contributor to ''[[The Guardian]]'', which began back in 2007 with his [[Slow Traveller]] blog.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/series/slowtraveller |title=Slow Traveller &#124; From the Observer |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> This developed into commentary on topics around sustainable business, climate change and environmental communications.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/ed-gillespie|title=Ed Gillespie|date=2009-01-04|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Wild Things Publishing published Ed's first book, ''[[Only Planet (book)|Only Planet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlyplanet.co.uk |title=Only Planet |publisher=Only Planet |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/only-planet-by-ed-gillespie-book-review-allow-worlds-flaws-and-beauty-to-seep-into-your-soul-9532757.html|title=Only Planet by Ed Gillespie, book review: Allow world's flaws and|last=Webb|first=Flemmich|date=2014-06-12|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-10-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> The book is based on his 2007/8 trip and the Independent described it as allowing 'the world's flaws and beauty to seep into your soul'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/only-planet-by-ed-gillespie-book-review-allow-worlds-flaws-and-beauty-to-seep-into-your-soul-9532757.html|title=Only Planet by Ed Gillespie, book review: Allow world's flaws and|date=2014-06-12|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nGillespie is regularly invited to lecture around the world to audiences, including the [[UN]], national governments, [[multinational corporation]]s and citizen organizations. He has given two [[TEDx]] talks, the first in 2010 about the importance of embedding sustainability into business strategy in a talk titled 'Sustainability, the reinvention of progress'<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vlearn.org/responsible-marketing/ |title=Responsible Marketing |publisher=VLearn.org |accessdate=2015-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219151110/http://vlearn.org/responsible-marketing/ |archive-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the second in Hackney in 2015 on the future of food in 'We literally are what we eat'.<ref>{{Citation|title=We literally are what we eat {{!}} Ed Gillespie {{!}} TEDxHackney|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZJeI2VIEDY8|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nEd is increasingly interested in the power of creative writing to inspire change, writes poetry and publishes other articles on [https://medium.com/@edgillespie2018 his Medium page].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gillespie, Ed}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British environmentalists]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:Sustainability advocates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Wales]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Heriot-Watt University]]\n[[Category:People from Norfolk]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Edward Roger Martin Gillespie\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = 28 June 1972{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n| birth_place   = {{Nowrap|Norfolk, England, UK{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}}}\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Inspirational keynote speaker and futurist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Co-Founded wearefuterra.com, Director of Greenpeace UK\n| notable_works = wearefuterra.com\n}}\n\n'''Ed Gillespie''' is a British environmental entrepreneur, inspirational keynote speaker, futurist and author. His focus is on [[sustainability]] and innovation. \n\n==Early life and education==\n\nHe grew up in Norfolk, attending Norwich School. Afterwards he was a volunteer for [[Project Trust]] as a teacher in Above Rocks, [[Jamaica]]. He completed an BSc in [[marine biology]] at the [[University of Wales]] and continued in this discipline by undertaking a MSc in Marine Resource Development and Protection at [[Heriot-Watt University]].\n\nAfter this his focus shifted to business as he enrolled in a Professional Masters in Leadership for Sustainable Development at [[Middlesex University]], a course run by sustainable development charity Forum for the Future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forumforthefuture.org/masters-course-f4fma |title=Leadership for Sustainable Development |publisher=Forum for the Future |accessdate=2015-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219144138/https://www.forumforthefuture.org/masters-course-f4fma |archive-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While there he met Townsend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/small-business-network/2017/sep/20/businesses-on-the-couch-the-co-founders-in-couples-therapy|title=Businesses on the couch: the co-founders in couples' therapy|last=Lock|first=Helen|date=2017-09-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-10-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nEd started his professional career as an Environmental Development Manager at [[Transport for London|London Transport]]. Before this he had worked for the Survival [[Natural History]] Film Unit and as a [[marine biologist]] in [[Australia]], [[New Caledonia]] and [[Orkney]].\n\nIn 2001, he co-founded Futerra Sustainability Communications with [[Solitaire Townsend]]. He left the business in January 2019<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/small-business-network/2017/sep/20/businesses-on-the-couch-the-co-founders-in-couples-therapy|title=Businesses on the couch: the co-founders in couples' therapy|last=Lock|first=Helen|date=2017-09-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> to pursue other radical opportunities in international public speaking through the London Speaker Bureau<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://londonspeakerbureau.com/speaker-profile/ed-gillespie/|website=londonspeakerbureau.com|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, with the Forward Institute - where he works as a facilitator on responsible leadership development<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forward.institute/team-board|title=Team & Board|website=Forward Institute|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> and with disruptive, purpose-led start-up businesses including through his own ethical business accelerator<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearefuterra.com/2018/06/global-goals-accelerator/|title=Global Goals Accelerator \u22c6 Futerra|date=2018-06-25|website=Futerra|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2007/8, he traveled around the world without flying, during which he wrote a regular popular column for the Guardian/Observer - 'The Slow Traveller'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2007/mar/18/green.ethicalholidays.escape|title=The slow traveller: A bumpy start|last=Gillespie|first=Ed|date=2007-03-18|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>. His passion for slow travel led him to invest in, and become Chairman of, European Rail Business [[Loco2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://loco2.com/about/team |title=team |publisher=Loco2 |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> This business was sold to SNCF in 2017<ref>{{Citation|title=Loco2|date=2019-11-06|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Loco2&oldid=924860107|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>. \n\nEd has held a number of Senior Advisory positions and Directorships. These include as a non-executive Director for Zero Carbon Food,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerocarbonfood.co.uk/team/ |title=The Team &#124; Zero Carbon FoodZero Carbon Food |publisher=Zerocarbonfood.co.uk |date=2014-01-24 |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> he was a London Sustainable Development Commissioner for several years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonsdc.org/lsdc/commissioners/ed-gillespie.aspx |title=Ed Gillespie |publisher=Londonsdc.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>  was a Director of carbon emissions campaigning organisation [[Sandbag (non-profit organisation)|Sandbag]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandbag.org.uk/whoweare/ |title=Who we are |publisher=Sandbag |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326040618/http://www.sandbag.org.uk/whoweare/ |archive-date=26 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and an investor in Foodtrade.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.foodtrade.com/frucool/ |title=ed gillespie |publisher=FoodTrade |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHe is currently a Director at Greenpeace UK<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenpeace.org.uk/about-greenpeace/board-of-directors/|title=Board of directors|website=Greenpeace UK|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, a Trustee at Energy Revolution<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.energy-revolution.org.uk/trustees/ed-gillespie/|title=Ed Gillespie|website=Energy Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> and an investor in a wide range of 'gamechanging' entrepreneurial businesses including Panda Packaging<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pandapackaging.co.uk/|website=www.pandapackaging.co.uk|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, Piclo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://piclo.energy/|title=piclo.energy|website=piclo.energy|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, Raw Bottles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://raw-bottles.org/|title=RAW Bottles|website=Realising Another World|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, Bennaman<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bennamann.com/|title=Bennamann Ltd \u2013 Bennamann creates solutions that transform the biomethane value chain.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, Engaged Tracking<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engagedtracking.com/|title=Engaged Tracking {{!}} Climate Portfolio Optimisation|website=EngagedTracking|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>, Common  Objective<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commonobjective.co/|title=Sustainable Fashion {{!}} Do Fashion Better {{!}} Common Objective|website=www.commonobjective.co|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref> and Small Robot Company<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smallrobotcompany.com/|title=Small Robot Company|website=Small Robot Company|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>. \n\nAlong with fellow futurist [[Mark Stevenson]] he is half of the Futurenauts at the [https://www.atlasofthefuture.org Atlas of the Future,] and has both [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V8oYY_S8q7k spoken at] and co-hosted their annual [https://atlasofthefuture.org/fixing2019/ Fixing the Future] event in Barcelona. \n\n== Publications and public speaking ==\nEd is a regular contributor to ''[[The Guardian]]'', which began back in 2007 with his [[Slow Traveller]] blog.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/series/slowtraveller |title=Slow Traveller &#124; From the Observer |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref> This developed into commentary on topics around sustainable business, climate change and environmental communications.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/ed-gillespie|title=Ed Gillespie|date=2009-01-04|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Wild Things Publishing published Ed's first book, ''[[Only Planet (book)|Only Planet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlyplanet.co.uk |title=Only Planet |publisher=Only Planet |date= |accessdate=2015-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/only-planet-by-ed-gillespie-book-review-allow-worlds-flaws-and-beauty-to-seep-into-your-soul-9532757.html|title=Only Planet by Ed Gillespie, book review: Allow world's flaws and|last=Webb|first=Flemmich|date=2014-06-12|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-10-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> The book is based on his 2007/8 trip and the Independent described it as allowing 'the world's flaws and beauty to seep into your soul'<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/only-planet-by-ed-gillespie-book-review-allow-worlds-flaws-and-beauty-to-seep-into-your-soul-9532757.html|title=Only Planet by Ed Gillespie, book review: Allow world's flaws and|date=2014-06-12|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>. \n\nGillespie is regularly invited to lecture around the world to audiences, including the [[UN]], national governments, [[multinational corporation]]s and citizen organizations. He has given two [[TEDx]] talks, the first in 2010 about the importance of embedding sustainability into business strategy in a talk titled 'Sustainability, the reinvention of progress'<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vlearn.org/responsible-marketing/ |title=Responsible Marketing |publisher=VLearn.org |accessdate=2015-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219151110/http://vlearn.org/responsible-marketing/ |archive-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the second in Hackney in 2015 on the future of food in 'We literally are what we eat'<ref>{{Citation|title=We literally are what we eat {{!}} Ed Gillespie {{!}} TEDxHackney|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZJeI2VIEDY8|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>.\n\nEd is increasingly interested in the power of creative writing to inspire change, writes poetry and publishes other articles on [https://medium.com/@edgillespie2018 his Medium page].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gillespie, Ed}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British environmentalists]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction environmental writers]]\n[[Category:Sustainability advocates]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Wales]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Heriot-Watt University]]\n[[Category:People from Norfolk]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_Gillespie_(sustainability_professional)"}
{"title_page": "Philippe Djian", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Philippe Djian\n| image         = Philippe Djian 2009.jpg\n| caption       = Philippe Djian in 2009\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1949|6|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| occupation    = [[Novelist]]\n| language      = French\n| nationality   = French\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Ecole Sup\u00e9rieure de Journalisme de Paris|ESJ Paris]]\n| period        = 1981\u2013present\n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''37\u00b02 le matin''\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] (2012)\n| signature     = \n| module        =\n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Philippe Djian''' ({{IPA-fr|filip d\u0292j\u0251\u0303|lang}}; born 3 June 1949) is a popular [[French literature|French author]] of [[Armenian people|Armenian]] descent. He won the 2012 [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] for the novel ''\"Oh...\" (Elle'' <ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.otherpress.com/books/elle/|title=Elle|last=|first=|publisher=Other Press|year=2017|isbn=978-1-59051-916-5|location=New York|pages=http://www.otherpress.com/books/elle/|language=en-US}}</ref> for the English translation)<!--title includes quotes-->.<ref name=larminat/><ref name=lexpress2012/>\n\n==Life and career==\nDjian graduated from the [[Ecole Sup\u00e9rieure de Journalisme de Paris|ESJ Paris]]. After a period of wandering and odd jobs, he published a volume of short stories, ''50 contre 1'' (1981), and then the novels ''Bleu comme l'enfer'' (1982) and ''Zone \u00e9rog\u00e8ne'' (1984) before gaining fame with his subsequent novels ''37\u00b02 le matin'' (1985), ''Maudit Man\u00e8ge'' (1986), ''Echine'' (1988), ''Crocodiles'' (short stories) (1989), ''Lent dehors'' (1991), ''Sotos'' (1993), and ''Assassins'' (1994).\n\nFive of his novels have been adapted into films: ''37\u00b02 le matin'' (1986; English title ''[[Betty Blue]]'') which was filmed by Jean-Jacques Beineix, ''Bleu comme l'enfer'' (1986; English title ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Bleu comme l'enfer|fr|3=Bleu comme l'enfer|lt=Blue Hell}}'') directed by Yves Boisset; ''Impardonnables'' (2011; English title [[Unforgivable (2011 film)|''Unforgivable'']]) directed by [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]; ''[[Love Is the Perfect Crime]]'' (2013; original title ''L'Amour est un crime parfait'') directed by [[Arnaud Larrieu]] and [[Jean-Marie Larrieu]]; and ''Oh...'' (as ''[[Elle (film)|Elle]]'' (2016) directed by [[Paul Verhoeven]]). He also co-wrote the screenplay of ''Ne fais pas \u00e7a'' (2004) with Luc Bondy.\n\nThe TV presenter [[Antoine De Caunes]] introduced him to Swiss singer [[Stephan Eicher]]. The two men became friends and Djian became the writer of Eicher's lyrics, at least for the songs in French.\n\nDjian frequently moved (from [[Boston]] to [[Florence]]). Today he lives in [[Biarritz]] and, on average, writes a novel every 18 months. With ''Doggy Bag'', written in 2005, he started a literary series with six seasons, inspired by American TV series.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*2009 [[Prix Jean-Freusti\u00e9]] for ''Impardonnables''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.prix-litteraires.net/prix/69,prix-jean-freustie.html |title= Prix Jean Freusti\u00e9 |language=French |accessdate=June 5, 2009}}</ref>\n*2012 [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] for ''\"Oh...\"''<ref name=larminat>{{cite web |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2012/11/14/03005-20121114ARTFIG00579-philippe-djian-prix-interallie.php |title=Philippe Djian, prix Interalli\u00e9 |work=[[Le Figaro]] |author=Astrid De Larminat |language=French |date=November 14, 2012 |accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref><ref name=lexpress2012>{{cite web |url=http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/livre/le-prix-interallie-pour-philippe-djian_1186054.html |title=VIDEO. Le prix Interalli\u00e9 pour Philippe Djian |work=[[L'Express (France)|L'Express]] |author=[[Staff writer]] |language=French |date=November 14, 2012 |accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Novels===\n*''[[Bleu comme l'enfer (novel)|Bleu comme l'enfer]]'' (1983; film: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Bleu comme l'enfer|fr|3=Bleu comme l'enfer|lt=Blue Hell}}'')\n*''Zone \u00e9rog\u00e8ne'' (1984)\n*''[[37\u02da2 le matin]]'' (1985; film: ''[[Betty Blue]]'')\n*''Maudit man\u00e8ge'' (1986)\n*''\u00c9chine'' (1988)\n*''[[Lent dehors]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Sotos]]'' (1993)\n*''Assassins'' (1994)\n*''Criminels'' (1997)\n*''Sainte Bob'' (1998)\n*''[[Vers chez les blancs]]'' (2000)\n*''\u00c7a c'est un baiser'' (2002)\n*''Frictions'' (2003)\n*''Impuret\u00e9s'' (2005)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 1'' (2005)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 2'' (2006)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 3'' (2006)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 4'' (2007)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 5'' (2007)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 6'' (2008)\n*''Impardonnables'' (2009; film: ''[[Unforgivable (2011 film)|Unforgivable]]'')\n*''Incidences'' (2010)\n*''Vengeances'' (2011)\n*''\"Oh...\"''  (Gallimard, 2012 - trans. as ''Elle'' by [[Michael Katims]], Other Press 2017) <!--title includes quotes-->\n*''Love Song'' (2013)\n*''Ch\u00e9ri-Ch\u00e9ri'' (2014)\n\n===Short stories===\n*''[[50 contre 1]]'' (1981)\n*''Crocodiles'' (1989)\n*''Lorsque Lou'' (1992)\n*''Contes de No\u00ebl'' (1996)\n*''Mise en bouche'' (2003)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/arts/headspace/rn/booksw/djian/default.htm Biography of Djian]\n*[http://zenbullets.com/blog/?p=87 Philippe Djian vs Betty Blue]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Djian, Philippe}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:French Armenians]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:Prix Interalli\u00e9 winners]]\n[[Category:Prix Jean Freusti\u00e9 winners]]\n[[Category:French lyricists]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure de journalisme de Paris alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Philippe Djian\n| image         = Philippe Djian 2009.jpg\n| caption       = Philippe Djian in 2009\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1949|6|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| occupation    = [[Novelist]]\n| language      = French\n| nationality   = French\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Ecole Sup\u00e9rieure de Journalisme de Paris|ESJ Paris]]\n| period        = 1981\u2013present\n| genre         = \n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = ''37\u00b02 le matin''\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] (2012)\n| signature     = \n| module        =\n| website       = <!-- www.example.com -->\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Philippe Djian''' ({{IPA-fr|filip d\u0292j\u0251\u0303|lang}}; born 3 June 1949) is a popular [[French literature|French author]] of [[Armenian people|Armenian]] descent. He won the 2012 [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] for the novel ''\"Oh...\" (Elle'' <ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.otherpress.com/books/elle/|title=Elle|last=|first=|publisher=Other Press|year=2017|isbn=978-1-59051-916-5|location=New York|pages=http://www.otherpress.com/books/elle/|language=en-US}}</ref> for the English translation)<!--title includes quotes-->.<ref name=larminat/><ref name=lexpress2012/>\n\n==Life and career==\nDjian graduated from the [[Ecole Sup\u00e9rieure de Journalisme de Paris|ESJ Paris]]. After a period of wandering and odd jobs, he published a volume of short stories, ''50 contre 1'' (1981), and then the novels ''Bleu comme l'enfer'' (1982) and ''Zone \u00e9rog\u00e8ne'' (1984) before gaining fame with his subsequent novels ''37\u00b02 le matin'' (1985), ''Maudit Man\u00e8ge'' (1986), ''Echine'' (1988), ''Crocodiles'' (short stories) (1989), ''Lent dehors'' (1991), ''Sotos'' (1993), and ''Assassins'' (1994).\n\nFive of his novels have been adapted into films: ''37\u00b02 le matin'' (1986; English title ''[[Betty Blue]]'') which was filmed by Jean-Jacques Beineix, ''Bleu comme l'enfer'' (1986; English title ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Bleu comme l'enfer|fr|3=Bleu comme l'enfer|lt=Blue Hell}}'') directed by Yves Boisset; ''Impardonnables'' (2011; English title [[Unforgivable (2011 film)|''Unforgivable'']]) directed by [[Andr\u00e9 T\u00e9chin\u00e9]]; ''[[Love Is the Perfect Crime]]'' (2013; original title ''L'Amour est un crime parfait'') directed by [[Arnaud Larrieu]] and [[Jean-Marie Larrieu]]; and ''Oh...'' (as ''[[Elle (film)|Elle]]'' (2016) directed by [[Paul Verhoeven]]). He also co-wrote the screenplay of ''Ne fais pas \u00e7a'' (2004) with Luc Bondy.\n\nThe TV presenter [[Antoine De Caunes]] introduced him to Swiss singer [[Stephan Eicher]]. The two men became friends and Djian became the writer of Eicher's lyrics, at least for the songs in French.\n\nDjian frequently moved (from [[Boston]] to [[Florence]]). Today he lives in [[Biarritz]] and, on average, writes a novel every 18 months. With ''Doggy Bag'', written in 2005, he started a literary series with six seasons, inspired by American TV series.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*2009 [[Prix Jean-Freusti\u00e9]] for ''Impardonnables''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.prix-litteraires.net/prix/69,prix-jean-freustie.html |title= Prix Jean Freusti\u00e9 |language=French |accessdate=June 5, 2009}}</ref>\n*2012 [[Prix Interalli\u00e9]] for ''\"Oh...\"''<ref name=larminat>{{cite web |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2012/11/14/03005-20121114ARTFIG00579-philippe-djian-prix-interallie.php |title=Philippe Djian, prix Interalli\u00e9 |work=[[Le Figaro]] |author=Astrid De Larminat |language=French |date=November 14, 2012 |accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref><ref name=lexpress2012>{{cite web |url=http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/livre/le-prix-interallie-pour-philippe-djian_1186054.html |title=VIDEO. Le prix Interalli\u00e9 pour Philippe Djian |work=[[L'Express (France)|L'Express]] |author=[[Staff writer]] |language=French |date=November 14, 2012 |accessdate=November 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Novels===\n*''[[Bleu comme l'enfer (novel)|Bleu comme l'enfer]]'' (1983; film: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Bleu comme l'enfer|fr|3=Bleu comme l'enfer|lt=Blue Hell}}'')\n*''Zone \u00e9rog\u00e8ne'' (1984)\n*''[[37\u02da2 le matin]]'' (1985; film: ''[[Betty Blue]]'')\n*''Maudit man\u00e8ge'' (1986)\n*''\u00c9chine'' (1988)\n*''[[Lent dehors]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Sotos]]'' (1993)\n*''Assassins'' (1994)\n*''Criminels'' (1997)\n*''Sainte Bob'' (1998)\n*''[[Vers chez les blancs]]'' (2000)\n*''\u00c7a c'est un baiser'' (2002)\n*''Frictions'' (2003)\n*''Impuret\u00e9s'' (2005)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 1'' (2005)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 2'' (2006)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 3'' (2006)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 4'' (2007)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 5'' (2007)\n*''Doggy bag, saison 6'' (2008)\n*''Impardonnables'' (2009; film: ''[[Unforgivable (2011 film)|Unforgivable]]'')\n*''Incidences'' (2010)\n*''Vengeances'' (2011)\n*''\"[http://www.otherpress.com/books/elle/ Oh...]\"''  (Gallimard, 2012 - trans. as ''Elle'' by [[Michael Katims]], Other Press 2017) <!--title includes quotes-->\n*''Love Song'' (2013)\n*''Ch\u00e9ri-Ch\u00e9ri'' (2014)\n\n===Short stories===\n*''[[50 contre 1]]'' (1981)\n*''Crocodiles'' (1989)\n*''Lorsque Lou'' (1992)\n*''Contes de No\u00ebl'' (1996)\n*''Mise en bouche'' (2003)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.abc.net.au/arts/headspace/rn/booksw/djian/default.htm Biography of Djian]\n*[http://zenbullets.com/blog/?p=87 Philippe Djian vs Betty Blue]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Djian, Philippe}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:French Armenians]]\n[[Category:20th-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French novelists]]\n[[Category:Prix Interalli\u00e9 winners]]\n[[Category:Prix Jean Freusti\u00e9 winners]]\n[[Category:French lyricists]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure de journalisme de Paris alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Zedembee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNovels:'Oh....' ('Elle') book link is to a publisher's page that appears to be outdated (no mention of the book on it)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philippe_Djian"}
